You write one compact external markdown continuity-memory entry for long
document translation.

This memory is used only for later translation continuity:
- section flow and document progression
- discourse state and open references
- tone, register, structure, and compactness of labels
- durable relationships/dependencies among people, organizations, institutions,
  systems, policies, procedures, concepts, or document states when later scopes
  need those relationships to interpret meaning or register

Pre-translation analysis stores initial participant/role/dependency context.
This entry should record only changed, refined, or newly active continuity that
later scopes may need. If a relationship/register pattern changes during the
completed scope, record the change under Target register notes or Discourse
state, not as a glossary item.

Do not create glossary rules. Do not lock terminology. Do not recommend term
translations. Do not include source-target term mappings. Document Term Memory
handles terminology.
Do not write lines such as "A -> B", "A = B", "A: B", "translate A as B",
or "{{ target_lang }} translation for A is B". If a note would only say how a
term was translated, omit it.

Write only durable continuity information that a later, different scope may
need. Avoid verbose local detail, routine dialogue, table rows, examples, and
terminology.
If a relationship or dependency affects later interpretation, put it in the
most relevant existing field:
- source_flow: source-side entity/institution/procedure/concept relationships
  that affect document progression
- target_register_notes: relationship-based register or speech-level patterns,
  including dialogue register when applicable; note how speech level should
  shift when relationships, status, trust, intimacy, authority, or ritual
  formality changes
- discourse_state: unresolved or active relationships/dependencies that drive
  the next scope
- open_references: only unresolved references or states that later scopes must
  resolve; do not put general register notes here

Use only these canonical markdown labels after the application formats the
entry: Source flow, Target register notes, Style continuity, Discourse state,
Open references, Memory reason. Do not invent labels such as Narrative Arc,
Style & Tone, Character Labels, or Open References for Continuity.

Return compact JSON only.

<TARGET_LANGUAGE>
{{ target_lang }}
</TARGET_LANGUAGE>

<DOCUMENT_FORMAT>
{{ doc_format }}
</DOCUMENT_FORMAT>

<COMPLETED_SCOPE>
{{ scope }}
</COMPLETED_SCOPE>

<SECTION_TITLE>
{{ section_title }}
</SECTION_TITLE>

<STORE_REASON>
{{ reason }}
</STORE_REASON>

<RELEVANT_EXISTING_MARKDOWN_MEMORY>
{{ existing_memory_excerpt }}
</RELEVANT_EXISTING_MARKDOWN_MEMORY>

<COMPLETED_SCOPE_OBSERVATIONS format="json">
{{ scope_items | tojson }}
</COMPLETED_SCOPE_OBSERVATIONS>

Return JSON with this shape:
{
  "memory_entry": {
    "source_flow": "Concise source-side content and document progression to remember.",
    "target_register_notes": "Concise target-side register/structure notes, including relationship-based speech/register patterns when relevant. No term translations or source-target mappings.",
    "style_continuity": "Tone, register, sentence style, compact labels, or structural continuity.",
    "discourse_state": "Open topic, unresolved references, section progression, or active relationships/dependencies.",
    "open_references": ["Short unresolved reference/state that later scopes must resolve"]
  }
}
